ther parts of the world that bear the responsibility of protecting the majority of the world’s refugees. By focusing on Jordan, a Global South state that hosts the world’s second-largest number of refugees per capita, this book provides insights to consider alternate ways to handle the situation of refugees elsewhere. In the process, Culcasi brings the reader into refugees’ diverse realities through their own words, inherently arguing against the tendency of many people in the Global North to see refugees as aberrant, burdensome, or threatening.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman territorialityzMiddle East. 0aPalestinian ArabszJordanxSocial conditions. 0aRefugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.zJordan. 0aRefugeeszJordanxAttitudes. 0aRefugeeszJordan. 0aRefugeeszPalestine. 0aRefugeeszSyria. 0aSyrianszJordanxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aGlobal North, Global South, state territorial nexus, displacement, lived experiences, refugees, humanizing, Jordan, Palestinian refugees, Syrian refugees.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226827056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226827056/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles